From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: amd-epyc-spike <s@s>
Date: Thu, 17 Jul 2026 16:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] KVM: SVM: KVM_EXIT_PREEMPT in-kernel force-exit analogue (AE-3)

The AMD/SVM analogue of the x86/VMX deterministic in-kernel force-exit
(consonance/vmm-backend/kvm-patches/patches/0004-KVM-x86-add-KVM_EXIT_PREEMPT-...).
docs/AMD-EPYC.md AE-3 / harmony tasks/123. VALIDATED-ON-SILICON (see BUILD STATUS).

The determinism ABI is substrate-agnostic ABOVE the interrupt-delivery detail: a
retired-taken-branch perf_event (ex_ret_brn_tkn, Zen PMCx0C4) armed at
deadline - SKID_MARGIN overflows and fires a host PMI; the in-kernel force-exit
converts that overflow into a deterministic vCPU exit with a dedicated reason
BEFORE any guest-visible side effect, so the V-time deadline is hit with only the
bounded hardware-PMI skid rather than the unbounded SIGIO-delivery skid a
CPU-bound guest can outrun (AE-1(d) measured the hardware PMI skid at max 5043
retired taken branches; this patch is what lands at it deterministically).

TWO HUNKS (the AMD delta vs the shared x86 plumbing). Intel and AMD are the SAME
x86-64 Arch and share arch/x86 (docs/ARCH-BOUNDARY.md): the UAPI (KVM_EXIT_PREEMPT;
KVM_ARM_PREEMPT_EXIT ioctl), the per-vCPU one-shot arm (vcpu->arch.preempt_armed),
the ioctl case in arch/x86/kvm/x86.c, the kvm->arch.deterministic_intercepts field
and its KVM_ENABLE_CAP handler are ALL added by the vendor-neutral x86 patches
0001/0002/0004 and shared verbatim with VMX. This patch adds the two things those
patches do NOT provide for SVM:

  (1) svm.c nmi_interception() hook — the analogue of 0004's vmx.c
      handle_exception_nmi() is_nmi() arm. On overflow the PMI arrives as an NMI,
      #VMEXITs SVM_EXIT_NMI (serviced by svm_handle_exit_irqoff()), and this makes
      nmi_interception() return to userspace with KVM_EXIT_PREEMPT when the opt-in
      and one-shot arm are set, instead of returning 1 (re-enter). default-off =>
      byte-identical stock behavior.

  (2) svm_hardware_setup(): kvm_caps.has_deterministic_intercepts = true — the
      analogue of patch 0003's `kvm_caps.has_deterministic_intercepts = true` in
      vmx_hardware_setup(). *** THIS WAS THE MISSING PIECE (found on-silicon,
      tasks/123 AE-3). *** Patch 0003 that advertises the opt-in is VMX-only; with
      only hunk (1), KVM_ENABLE_CAP(KVM_CAP_X86_DETERMINISTIC_INTERCEPTS) returns
      -EINVAL on an AMD host (kvm_vm_ioctl_enable_cap guards on
      kvm_caps.has_deterministic_intercepts), so the opt-in can never be set and the
      force-exit never arms. This one line is the SVM cap advertisement. (RDTSC/
      RDRAND/RDSEED *exiting* — 0003's other half — is NOT added here: that is AE-4
      contract enforcement, a separate SVM intercept-wiring concern; the force-exit
      needs only the opt-in flag + the NMI hook.)

ARCH DETAIL (svm.c vs vmx.c). On AMD SVM the perf-overflow PMI is delivered as an
NMI exactly as on Intel; with the VMCB NMI intercept set (KVM's default), the NMI
#VMEXITs with SVM_EXIT_NMI, the host PMI has already been serviced by
svm_handle_exit_irqoff() by the time nmi_interception() runs. AVIC does not
accelerate NMIs, so the perf-overflow NMI reaches this path regardless; AVIC-off
(kvm_amd avic=0) is a recorded standing determinism condition, attested per run.

BUILD STATUS (AE-3, tasks/123) — VALIDATED ON-SILICON 2026-07-17. Built into a
bootable linux-6.18.35 (host/build-6.18-kernel.sh) with the canonical determinism
series 0001-0005; both hunks git-apply clean to 6.18.35. Booted on the live box
(Ryzen 5 PRO 3600, Zen 2), patched kvm_amd loaded (avic=0, nested=1). The AE-3
harness (harness/ae3-forceexit.c) armed the ex_ret_brn_tkn overflow and the guest
exited with KVM_EXIT_PREEMPT (exit_reason 42) on every arm, work_at_preempt <=
target, skid in [2581,3039] << the 8192/16384 margin, never overshooting at the
overflow. The escalation (6.8-vs-6.18 kernel skew) is RESOLVED: the box was built
+ booted onto 6.18.35 per Paul's 2026-07-17 ruling. (Exact single-step LANDING has
a residual run-to-run counter jitter on the non-isolated core — see AE-3
disposition; the force-exit mechanism itself is solid.)

Co-developed-for: harmony AMD vendor spike AE-3 (tasks/123)
---
 arch/x86/kvm/svm/svm.c | 24 +++++++++++++++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 23 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/arch/x86/kvm/svm/svm.c b/arch/x86/kvm/svm/svm.c
index 000000000..000000001 100644
--- a/arch/x86/kvm/svm/svm.c
+++ b/arch/x86/kvm/svm/svm.c
@@ -2311,4 +2311,19 @@ static int nmi_interception(struct kvm_vcpu *vcpu)
 static int nmi_interception(struct kvm_vcpu *vcpu)
 {
-	return 1;
+	/*
+	 * Deterministic preemption (harmony tasks/123; AMD/SVM analogue of the x86
+	 * KVM_EXIT_PREEMPT force-exit, patch 0004's handle_exception_nmi() hunk).
+	 * The perf-overflow PMI arrived as an NMI, #VMEXIT'd with SVM_EXIT_NMI, and
+	 * was already serviced by svm_handle_exit_irqoff() by the time we run here.
+	 * If userspace armed the one-shot force-exit under the determinism opt-in,
+	 * return to userspace with KVM_EXIT_PREEMPT instead of re-entering, so the
+	 * V-time deadline is hit with only the bounded hardware-PMI skid. Gated on
+	 * the determinism opt-in => default-off is byte-identical stock behavior.
+	 */
+	if (vcpu->kvm->arch.deterministic_intercepts && vcpu->arch.preempt_armed) {
+		vcpu->arch.preempt_armed = false;
+		vcpu->run->exit_reason = KVM_EXIT_PREEMPT;
+		return 0;
+	}
+	return 1;
 }
@@ -5447,4 +5447,8 @@ static __init int svm_hardware_setup(void)
 	kvm_caps.max_tsc_scaling_ratio = SVM_TSC_RATIO_MAX;
 	kvm_caps.tsc_scaling_ratio_frac_bits = 32;
+	/*
+	 * harmony AE-3 (tasks/123): advertise the deterministic-intercepts opt-in on
+	 * SVM (patch 0003's vmx_hardware_setup line) so KVM_ENABLE_CAP for
+	 * KVM_CAP_X86_DETERMINISTIC_INTERCEPTS succeeds and the force-exit arms.
+	 */
+	kvm_caps.has_deterministic_intercepts = true;

 	tsc_aux_uret_slot = kvm_add_user_return_msr(MSR_TSC_AUX);
--
2.47.3
